#introduction
Discover variadic functions in C.
Well-structured & extensible code.

Once you pass this assignment,
you will be able to add your ft_printf() to your libft.

#mandatory

table:
Program name		libftprintf.a
Turn in files		Makefile, *.h, */*.h, *.c, */*.c
Makefile			NAME, all, clean, fclean, re
External functs.	malloc, free, write,
					va_start, va_arg, va_copy, va_end
Libft authorized	Yes
Description			Write a library that contains ft_printf(), a
					function that will mimic the original printf()

prototype: int	ft_printf(const char *, ...);

requirements:
do not implement buffer management.
handle these converstions: c,s,p,d,i,u,x,X,%
your function will be evaluated against the behavior of the original printf().
use ar command, not libtool
libftprintf.a must be at the root dir.

conversions:
%c: a single char.
%s: a string (as defined by the common C convention).
%p: the void * pointer argument in hexadecimal format.
%d: a decimal number.
%i: an integer in base 10.
%u: an unsigned decimal number.
%x: a number in hexadecimal lowercase format.
%X: a numebr in hexadecimal uppercase format.
%%: '%'.

#memo

".. a function that will mimic the original printf()"
it's "mimic" but "re-implement".

both %d and %i give the same behavior.
%% is not conversion (maybe no arg for this).


